the call who, you know, work in this kind of stuff, as we know, the problem with modeling things based

00:26:59.859 --> 00:27:05.300
on demographics is, you know, the interests tend to cut across demographic lines, right? So I was

00:27:05.300 --> 00:27:12.020
used to saying Warner Brothers, you know, Batman fans are 8 to 80, you know? So you can have, you

00:27:12.020 --> 00:27:17.459
know, it cuts across lines, you know? And so it's the same thing with music. You know, I'll talk to

00:27:17.459 --> 00:27:22.260
people who are, you know, in their 20s and they'll be like, I love Lionel Richie, he's one of our artists,

00:27:22.260 --> 00:27:27.459
and, you know, I love Lionel Richie and, you know, his last big songs came out in like the 80s, right?

00:27:27.459 --> 00:27:32.099
Or I'll talk to people who are 65 and who are like, oh man, you know, you have Lionel Richie, we love

00:27:32.099 --> 00:27:38.339
Lionel Richie, right? And then tips and tricks, I would say, you know, it's important depending on

00:27:38.339 --> 00:27:42.900
the type of company you're at to think creatively about the types of data you use. I find that

00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:47.780
there's a little bit of a curse of data sometimes, where the bigger your internal data, the more

00:27:47.780 --> 00:27:53.459
