00:27:58.819 --> 00:28:05.060
decisions. And I would say that, you know, I spent a lot of time early on on Kaggle and, you know,

00:28:05.060 --> 00:28:09.459
that's really where I thought a lot about, you know, there were these competitions with external data.

00:28:09.459 --> 00:28:14.420
And, you know, it really taught me to think creatively about what other data could you bring

00:28:14.420 --> 00:28:18.660
to solve these problems. And whereas, you know, like when I would work in companies, I was like,

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:23.459
oh no, we have the Call of Duty data. We know everything everybody did on our platform.

00:28:23.459 --> 00:28:27.380
Why do we need additional data? And I'm like, well, we had a 20% drop in users and nothing

00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:31.699
changed in our game. And another competitive game came out. We should probably be seeing,

00:28:31.699 --> 00:28:34.900
you know, instead of assuming that it just came from that competitive game, getting additional

00:28:34.900 --> 00:28:39.459
data to see, you know, how many people are playing that game versus they're doing other things,

00:28:39.459 --> 00:28:45.780
right? And so it's really important to think about that as an important tip or trick, as you

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:50.500
will, to maybe a little bit more than a trick, but really a philosophy to think about how you apply

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:56.180
data science in whatever industry you're in, right, is to think about the source of your data

00:28:56.180 --> 00:29:00.339
and think about creatively, are there ways you can augment that data with other data sets from the

00:29:00.339 --> 00:29:08.819
outside? I remember Adam once brought SafeGraphs data to understand the mobility to solve

00:29:08.819 --> 00:29:15.619
problems in the studio, so I second him. Yes, Junaid was full disclaimer. Junaid was on my

00:29:15.619 --> 00:29:19.619
team a few years ago at Warner Brothers. I was just going to say, it seems like you both know

00:29:19.619 --> 00:29:28.180
each other. I mean, I love when there's something that so many people can relate to, like music,

00:29:28.180 --> 00:29:34.260
there's so many awesome questions coming in. George, you had asked a question a little bit

00:29:34.260 --> 00:29:38.260
earlier about when things don't meet your expectations. Do you want to jump in?

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:49.699
And I can read it if you want to add context, feel free. But it's, what are some examples of when

00:29:49.699 --> 00:29:54.819
results of your analysis went against the expectations of the artist? How do artists

00:29:54.819 --> 00:29:58.579
and or their management react to data that goes against their assumptions?

00:29:59.859 --> 00:30:03.060
That's a great question. I would say that that's not just in music, that's everywhere,

00:30:03.780 --> 00:30:09.859
where, you know, when you think about it, sometimes as data professionals, we are the

00:30:09.859 --> 00:30:14.979
bearer of bad news. And sometimes we're the bearer of something unexpected, which could be really

00:30:14.979 --> 00:30:21.300
exciting. And so it's a double-edged sword, right? I think the, you know, where something didn't go

00:30:21.300 --> 00:30:25.619
their way, right, or something wasn't what they're expecting, I would say in music, people are pretty

00:30:25.619 --> 00:30:32.339
positive. Like, you know, it's not that difficult to produce new music. You're not spending hundreds

00:30:32.339 --> 00:30:36.900
of millions of dollars on it, like a film. I would say it was a lot tougher in film and TV.

00:30:36.900 --> 00:30:40.660
Like, if you're working on a marketing campaign for a film where we've already spent $150 million,

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:45.939
we're spending $50 million to market this film, and like, no one is showing any interest in seeing

00:30:45.939 --> 00:30:51.939
this film. But it's, those are tough conversations to have, where you have to go, like, I'm sorry,

00:30:51.939 --> 00:30:55.939
I know that we're really optimistic about this movie, but the numbers clearly indicate that,

00:30:56.900 --> 00:31:01.699
you know, we are way behind on presales, from where we should be. We want this to open to $100

00:31:01.699 --> 00:31:07.380
billion. And, you know, those are tough conversations to have. I will say that

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:14.579
it's one of those things where I have learned that different people respond to that information in

00:31:14.579 --> 00:31:18.579
different ways, and you have to be attuned to that type of person, and understand what type of person

00:31:18.579 --> 00:31:24.979
you're communicating with. Some people, you know, they're very receptive, and they're open. And with

00:31:24.979 --> 00:31:28.339
those people, it's good to share additional context, and, you know, make sure they understand

00:31:28.339 --> 00:31:33.939
why other people, they shut down, become very defensive, and feel like you're attacking them.

00:31:33.939 --> 00:31:38.420
And so if it's that kind of person, you have to be very careful when sharing negative information.

00:31:38.420 --> 00:31:43.699
Don't only share positive information, that's a mistake. But you may need to, like, couch it in

00:31:43.699 --> 00:31:48.660
softer terms, and make sure that you, you know, give something that seems more like a balanced

00:31:48.660 --> 00:31:53.219
perspective. Don't just give all negative news. Say, look, you know, there are some positives

00:31:53.219 --> 00:31:58.020
here, but there's also some negatives you should pay attention to. And then that might be more

00:31:58.020 --> 00:32:04.900
well received by someone who has a penchant for, for being more standoffish or defensive when they

00:32:04.900 --> 00:32:15.540
hear negative news. Thank you. Stephen, you had a question about earlier that touched on, like,

