aggregated and a helpful view. And then, sorry, the second part of the question was.

00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:21.540
It was basically saying, you know, I do a lot of, in my work, I do a lot of education related to,

00:34:22.419 --> 00:34:27.060
you know, data. So, so how, how do you explain these things to people without having to take

00:34:27.060 --> 00:34:34.020
up all your time, you know? Yeah. So I would say that it's a combination of when we roll out

00:34:34.020 --> 00:34:38.100
the tools to people, we kind of walk them through how they work and educate them a little bit. And

00:34:38.100 --> 00:34:43.939
we always answer questions or do follow-ups and that's helpful. You know, I have a neuroscience

00:34:43.939 --> 00:34:47.459
background from my time at UC San Diego. And so one of the most important things we learn in

00:34:47.459 --> 00:34:53.860
neuroscience is, you know, that the repetition really breeds learning. And so, you know,

00:34:53.860 --> 00:34:57.780
you want to strengthen those neural connections between the different areas. And so it's important

00:34:57.780 --> 00:35:00.979
to have follow-ups and touch bases and make sure that people are finding it useful.

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:06.179
And then reinforcing those concepts and tying things together is another way that, you know,

00:35:06.179 --> 00:35:10.659
really helps with learning. You know, if you have one concept, you understand you tie things to that

00:35:10.659 --> 00:35:15.780
concept. You know, there's a concept of like a neural attractor, but basically like you can think

00:35:15.780 --> 00:35:19.459
